SIMPLE: oblation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Oblation
<hw>Ob*la"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>oblatio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>oblation</ets>. See
<er>Oblate</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of offering, or of
making an offering.</def> <rj><au>Locke.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Anything offered or presented in worship or sacred
service; an offering; a sacrifice.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A peculiar . . . <qex>oblation</qex> given to God.</q>
<rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A pin was the usual <qex>oblation</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir. W.
Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A gift or contribution made to a church, as for the
expenses of the eucharist, or for the support of the clergy and the
poor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Oblationer</ent>⟦br⟧
